entry.name: warn_user_overrides_wsdl
entry.text: WSDL definitions for type %s ignored. Using user-supplied schema definition.
entry.description: When compiling a WSDL, user-supplied versions of transport (SOAP) schemas can override or partially override the built-in versions in the store: directory by importing them directly into the WSDL. While combining the definitions in the WSDL with built-in and user-supplied transport schema information, the compiler encountered a user-supplied transport type (for example soap:Body or soap:Header) that is more restrictive or unrelated to what the WSDL implies. As a result, the relevant WSDL definitions for only that type were ignored in favor of the user-supplied version.
entry.suggestion: This message might indicate that the user-supplied version of the transport type is constructed improperly. If the desired behavior is for the WSDL definitions to prevail, the user-supplied schema should be either removed or made more general.

entry.name: warn_wsdl_overrides_user
entry.text: WSDL definitions for type %s override user-supplied schema definition.
entry.description: When compiling a WSDL, user-supplied versions of transport (SOAP) schemas can override or partially override the built-in versions in the store: directory by importing them directly into the WSDL. While combining the definitions in the WSDL with built-in and user-supplied transport schema information, the compiler encountered a user-supplied transport type (for example soap:Body or soap:Header) that is more restrictive or unrelated to what the WSDL implies. For backward compatibility, the user-supplied schema type was ignored in favor of the WSDL definitions.
entry.suggestion: This message might indicate that the user-supplied version of the transport type is constructed improperly or that the WSDL does not reflect the expected traffic. If the desired behavior is described by the user-schema, modify the WSDL to reflect the traffic.

entry.name: warn_component_precedence
entry.text: %1$s %2$s %3$s overrides %4$s version at %5$s.
entry.description: In a normal schema compilation, components with the same qualified name from different schema documents cannot conflict. When compiling a WSDL or during some special schema compilations, components that are implied by the WSDL (such as an rpc-wrapper element) or originate from a built-in schema (for example store:///schemas/soap-enevelope-1.1.xsd) might be overridden by user-supplied versions without error.
entry.suggestion: This message provides an alert that a built-in or implied component was overridden. If this is the desired behavior, ignore this message. Otherwise, the user-supplied version should be removed, or the import of the user-supplied schema should be removed from the WSDL or schema that imports it.

entry.name: schema_qnamenotimported
entry.text: QName %s references a namespace that is not imported by the enclosing schema document.
entry.description: XML Schema documents define named components in a specific target namespace (or no namespace if the targetNamespace attribute is not defined for that schema document). A schema document that references a component from a namespace other than the target namespace (if any) must contain an xsd:import element with a corresponding value for the namespace attribute. A schema document with a target namespace that references a component with no namespace must contain an xsd:import with no namespace attribute.
entry.suggestion: This message might be encountered because the QName is incorrect or because the namespace is not correctly imported. Either correct the QName or add an appropriate import element to the schema document.

entry.name: wsdl_docstyle_too_many_parts
entry.text: Document-style %1$s binds %2$zd parts of message %3$s, at most one is allowed.
entry.description: For document-style soap:body, soap:header, soap:fault, and soap:headerfault bindings, validation is only supported if the binding is constructed such that it binds at most one message part. This means that it must specify a part or parts attribute with at most one part listed, or must reference a message that defines at most one part.
entry.suggestion: Verify that the correct message is being referenced by the binding. If the intended message has several parts, the binding should be modified to use RPC/style (only for soap:body), or to bind only one part of the message. For SOAP headers, use several soap:header binding elements to bind each part as a separate header. Alternately, the message itself may be redefined such that all of the parts are wrapped in a single element.

entry.suggestion: Verify that the XML schema definition for the element has the correct type (typically xsd:base64Binary or an extension of it). Note that simpleTypes with constraining facets (patterns, length facets, and so forth) are not considered to be compatible with xop:Include.

entry.name: xopinclude_nootherchild

entry.description: While validating an MTOM/XOP optimized message, an xop:Include element was encountered in a simple type context, inside an element with other children. The xop:Include element may only be used to replace base64 encoded content that is the sole child of its parent element, and must completely replace that content. Therefore, no text, comments, processing instructions, or other elements are allowed surrounding the xop:Include element.

entry.suggestion: To allow MTOM/XOP optimized traffic, modify the Compile Options policy of the relevant XML manager or the policy toggles on the relevant Web Service Proxy to accept MTOM/XOP optimized XML.

entry.text: [JNTY0023] It is a dynamic error if, when calling jn:encode-for-roundtrip or jn:decode-from-roundtrip, the value of the option prefix is not atomizable and castable to a string, or if the value of the option serialization-parameters is not an element node.
entry.description: This is JSONiq error jerr:JNTY0023.
entry.suggestion: For more information, see the JSONiq specification.

entry.name: err_jnty0024
entry.text: [JNTY0024] Arrays and objects do not have a string value. It is a type error to call fn:string on an array or an object.
entry.description: This is JSONiq error jerr:JNTY0024.
entry.suggestion: For more information, see the JSONiq specification.

entry.name: err_jnst5000
entry.text: [JNST5000] It is a static error to use a JSONiq feature without the declare option jsoniq-version top-level declaration set to 0.4.42.
entry.description: This is Websphere JSONiq error jerr:JNST5000.
entry.suggestion: Add the top level declaration 'declare option jsoniq-version "0.4.42"'.

entry.name: err_jnty5001
entry.text: [JNST5001] It is a type error if the value of a property or an array is an XML node.
entry.description: This is Websphere JSONiq error jerr:JNST5001.
entry.suggestion: Change the constructed JSON property or array to be a JSON value.

entry.name: jn_function_wrong_num_args
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' is expecting '%2$d' arguments, but was called with '%3$d' arguments.
entry.description: A JSONata function is called with the wrong number of arguments.
entry.suggestion: Add or remove argument to call the function with the correct number of arguments.

entry.name: jn_parse_error
entry.text: The JSONata program did not parse, reason: '%1$s'
entry.description: A JSONata program did not parse as legal for the supported subset of JSONata.
entry.suggestion: Make sure that your JSONata is legal and that it is in the subset of JSONata supported by DataPower.

entry.name: jn_function_arg_wrong_type
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' is expecting argument number (0-based) '%2$d' to be of type '%3$s', but it was called with a value of type '%4$s'.
entry.description: A JSONata function is called with an argument in a position that requires a certain type but is called with a value of a different type..
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified argument produces a value of the correct type.

entry.name: jn_operand_wrong_type
entry.text: The JSONata operator '%1$s' is expecting operand number (0-based) '%2$d' to be of type '%3$s', but it was called with a value of type '%4$s'.
entry.description: A JSONata operator is called with an operand in a position that requires a certain type but is called with a value of a different type.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified operand produces a value of the correct type.

entry.name: jn_operand_not_simple
entry.text: The JSONata operator '%1$s' is expecting operand number (0-based) '%2$d' to be of a simple type (number, string, boolean, null) and not of a complex type (array, object, payload), and it found an operand of type '%3$s'.
entry.description: A JSONata operator is called with an operand in a position that requires a certain type but is called with a value of a different type.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified operand produces a value of the correct type.

entry.name: jn_operands_not_same_type
entry.text: The JSONata operator '%1$s' is expecting two operands of the same type, but operand number 0 (0-based) is of type '%2$s' and operand 1 (0-based) is of type '%3$s'.
entry.description: A JSONata operator is called with operands that are supposed to match type but do not.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified operands do match each other's type.

entry.name: jn_operand_type_not_supported
entry.text: The JSONata operator '%1$s' is expecting operand number (0-based) '%2$d' to be a different type, it found an operand of type '%3$s'.
entry.description: A JSONata operator is called with an operand of a type that is not supported.
entry.suggestion: Check the documentation for which types are supported in the subset of JSONata supported on DataPower for this operator. Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified operand is of a supported type.

entry.name: jn_parse_error_bad_function_name
entry.text: The JSONata program did not parse, reason: Unrecognized function name '%1$s' in function call.
entry.description: A JSONata program did not parse as legal because of encountering an unrecognized function name in a function call.
entry.suggestion: Check whether the function name is incorrect ond fix it to the proper function name.

entry.name: jn_number_wrong_type
entry.text: The JSONata function 'number' is expecting the argument to be of type 'number' or 'string', but it is called with a value of type '%1$s'.
entry.description: The JSONata function 'number' is called with the operand of a different type than expected.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified operand produces a value of the correct type.

entry.name: jn_number_wrong_value
entry.text: The JSONata function 'number' is expecting the argument to be a string representing a valid JSON number, but it is called with the value '%1$s'.
entry.description: The JSONata function 'number' is called with the operand of type 'string' containing value which can not be parsed into a JSON number.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified operand contains the correct value.

entry.name: jn_unexpected_runtime_error
entry.text: The JSONata runtime hit an unexpected condition.
entry.description: The JSONata runtime hit an unexpected condition.
entry.suggestion: Contact IBM Support and send what the JSONata program and input (context) are.

entry.name: jn_payload_type_not_supported
entry.text: The JSONata subset does not support inspecting message payloads.
entry.description: The JSONata subset does not support inspecting message payloads.
entry.suggestion: You can inspect metadata including headers and status code. A GatewayScript Policy can inspect the message payload or copy it elsewhere and then you can inspect it.

entry.name: jn_unsupported_escape_sequence
entry.text: Unsupported escape sequence: '\%1$c'.
entry.description: String literal is using unsupported escape sequence. The supported list contains '\\b', '\\f', '\\n', '\\r', '\\t', and '\\\\'
entry.suggestion: Change your JSONata program to use only supported escape sequences in string literals.

entry.name: jn_unrecognized_character
entry.text: Unrecognized character: '%1$c'.
entry.description: JSONata program included an unrecognized character which can not be parsed as part of the JSONata program..
entry.suggestion: Change your JSONata program to use only supported characters.

entry.name: jn_function_not_in_range_args
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' is expecting between '%2$d' and '%3$d' arguments, but was called with '%4$d' arguments.
entry.description: A JSONata function is called with the wrong number of arguments.
entry.suggestion: Add or remove argument to call the function with the correct number of arguments.

entry.name: jn_empty_string_arg
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' is unexpectedly called with an empty string as the argument number '%2$d' (0-based).
entry.description: A JSONata function is called with the string argument which cannot be an empty string.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified argument contains the correct value.

entry.name: jn_integer_not_in_range
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' is expecting integer argument number (0-based) '%2$d' to be in the range from %3$lld to %4$lld, but it was called with a value %5$lld.
entry.description: A JSONata function is called with an argument in a position that requires an integer value falling into a certain range but is called with a value outside of that range.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified argument produces a correct value.

entry.name: jn_positive_integer_arg

entry.description: A JSONata function is called with an argument in a position that requires a non-negative integer value but it is called with a negative one.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified argument produces a correct value.

entry.name: jn_strings_only_array_arg
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' is expecting array argument number (0-based) '%2$d' to contain only strings but the array item number (0-based) '%3$d' contains object of type '%4$s'.
entry.description: A JSONata function is called with an argument in a position that requires an array containing only string object but one of the items in the array has a different type.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the specified argument produces a correct value.

entry.name: jn_duplicate_regex_flag
entry.text: Duplicate regex flag found '%1$c' in regex argument given '%2$s'.
entry.description: Duplicate regex flags are not allowed.
entry.suggestion: Change your JSONata program to only contain one instance of each flag specified.

entry.name: jn_runtime_error_no_match
entry.text: The JSONata execution of the function '%1$s' did not find any matches for the regex argument given '%2$s'.
entry.description: At least one match needs to be found.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that at least one match is found.

entry.name: jn_arg_nan_or_infinity
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' can not be used with number value NaN or Infinity.
entry.description: Number values NaN and Infinity are not supported in JSON format.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the argument produces a correct value.

entry.name: jn_array_exceeded_size_limit
entry.text: The JSONata contains an array constructor exceeding the size limit '%1$ld'.
entry.description: The JSONata is configured to limit the size of generated arrays and that limit was exceeded.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the array size stays under the configured limit.

entry.name: jn_execution_exceeded_time_limit
entry.text: The JSONata execution exeeded the time limit of '%1$ld' seconds.
entry.description: The JSONata is configured to limit execution time and that limit was exceeded.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the execution time stays under the configured limit.

entry.name: jn_sort_not_same_type
entry.text: The JSONata function 'sort' is expecting array containing all elements of type '%1$s', but element number '%2$d' (0-based) is of type '%3$s'.
entry.description: The JSONata function 'sort' is called with the argument that is supposed to be an array contating elements of the same type but do not.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the argument to the function is of the appropriate type.

entry.name: jn_sort_type_not_supported
entry.text: The JSONata function 'sort' is expecting array containing either numbers or strings but the first element of the array is of type '%1$s'.
entry.description: The JSONata function 'sort' is called with an argument of a type that is not supported.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the argument to the function is of the supported type.

entry.name: jn_array_item_type_invalid

entry.description: The JSONata aggregation function is called with an array argument containing an invalid type.
entry.suggestion: Change either your JSONata program or the input to it so that the argument to the function is of the supported type.

entry.name: jn_value_out_of_range
entry.text: The JSONata function '%1$s' is expecting an argument number (0-based) '%2$d' to be between %3$lld and %4$lld, but it was called with a value %5$lld.
